"Abstract Public bodies have always been big purchasers of IT services, dealing as they do with huge, decentralized organizations with thousands of employees and budgets measured in the millions, if not the hundreds of millions. It is the very size of this market that makes them subject to the particular attention of the EU. Under Article 49 of the Treaty of Rome 1957 (as consolidated), the members of the European Union are required to provide freedom for the movement of services amongst the member states. For this reason, public procurement contracts must be made available to contractors across Europe. Recently, however, the procuring authorities in the UK have come under attack from both failed tenderers and the European Commission in respect of their method of adherence to these regulations. This article seeks to explore these criticisms and examine how they might affect the IT industry in the UK."
